# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. I declared a variable 'index' which is initialized to the value returned by the 'find()' function. The 'find()' function is called on the 'haystack' string and the 'needle' string is passed as an argument.
2. The 'find()' function returns the index of the first occurrence of the 'needle' string within the 'haystack' string. If the 'needle' string is not found within the 'haystack' string, the function returns a special constant 'string::npos'.
3. If 'index' is not equal to 'string::npos', it means that the 'needle' is found, so the 'index' is returned.
4. Else, -1 is returned, indicating that the 'needle' is not found in the 'haystack' string.
5. The 'strStr()' function returns the index of the first occurrence of the 'needle' string within the 'haystack' string.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this code is O(n) where n is the length of the haystack string. This is because the find function in the C++ STL library has an average time complexity of O(n).
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) as it only uses a constant amount of additional memory.


