solutions.content:
I will be providing with 3 solutions. The first one is a naive one, which actually runs quite good. Then I will be providing the linear time kmp and z-algorithm ones.

**Solution One**

This is a `Naive` implementation. Just check all substrings of length `m` in the haystack. If you get a substring, then just return the first index of the substring. I think the code is quite self explanatory.

```
int strStr(string haystack, string needle) {
	int n=haystack.length(), m=needle.length();
	for(int i=0;i<n-m+1;i++){
		int j=0;
		while(j<m){
			if(haystack[i+j]==needle[j]) j++;
			else break;
		}
		if(j==m) return i;
	}
	return -1;
}
```

*Time Complexity* - `O(m*(n-m+1))`
*Space Complexity* - `O(1)`

**Solution Two**

We use the famous KMP string matching algorithm, which does this in linear time. We have to pre-process and construct a `lps` array, where `lps[i]` denotes longest proper prefix which is also a suffix.
For more understanding of the KMP algo, follow these 3 links -

1. [Geeks for Geeks KMP Algo](https://www.***.org/kmp-algorithm-for-pattern-searching/)
2. [A blog describing KMP](https://blogarithms.github.io/articles/2018-06/kmp-algorithm)
3. Tushar Roy's video about KMP.

```
class Solution {
public:
    // calculate the lps function
    vector<int> calc(string pat, int m)
    {
        vector<int> lps(m,0);
        int i=1, j=0;
        while(i<m){
            if(pat[i]==pat[j]){
                j++;
                lps[i++]=j;
            }
            else{
                if(j) j=lps[j-1];
                else lps[i++]=0;
            }
        }
        return lps;
    }
    int strStr(string haystack, string needle) {
        int n=haystack.length(), m=needle.length();
        if(m==0) return 0;
        vector<int> lps = calc(needle, m);
        int i=0,j=0;
        while(i<n && j<m){
            if(haystack[i]==needle[j]){
                i++;
                j++;
            }
            if(j==m) return i-j; // since we are returning the first valid index, we just return i-j. If we had to return all valid indices, then we would have to do j=lps[j-1] after this step, since pattern can repeat, and the new pattern may already have started.
            else if(i<n && j<m && haystack[i]!=needle[j]){
                if(j) j=lps[j-1];
                else i++;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

*Time Complexity* - `O(m+n)`
*Space Complexity* - `O(m)`

**Solution Three**

We use the famous `Z Algorithm`, which is also a linear pattern matching algorithm. For this we have to construct a `Z-array` where `Z[i]` is equal to the longest substring starting from `S[i]`, which is also a prefix of the original string. We have to concatenate the pattern and the string together, along with a '$'.
For more info, follow these three links -

1. [Geeks for Geeks Z Algo](https://www.***.org/z-algorithm-linear-time-pattern-searching-algorithm/)
2. [HackerEarth Tutorial Z Algo](https://www.hackerearth.com/practice/algorithms/string-algorithm/z-algorithm/tutorial/)
3. Tushar Roy's video about Z Algo.

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> calc(string pat) // calculates the Z-array
    {
        int n=pat.length();
        vector<int> z(n,0);
        int L=0, R=0, i=1;
        for(;i<n;i++){
            if(i>R){  // i is not in the Z-box.
                L=R=i;
                while(R<n && pat[R-L]==pat[R]) R++;
                z[i]=R-L;
                R--;
            }
            else{
                int k=i-L;
                if(z[k]<R-i+1) z[i]=z[k];
                else{
                    L=i;
                    while(R<n && pat[R-L]==pat[R]) R++;
                    z[i]=R-L;
                    R--;
                }
            }
        }
        return z;
    }

    int strStr(string haystack, string needle) {
        int n=haystack.length(), m=needle.length();
        if(m==0) return 0;
        string res=needle+"$"+haystack;   // we find the z array for [pat + '$' + text]
        vector<int> z=calc(res);
        for(int i=0;i<res.length();i++){
            if(z[i]==m) return i-m-1;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

*Time Complexity* - `O(m+n)`
*Space Complexity* - `O(m+n)`

