First, the KMP with DFA(Deterministic Finite Automaton).
```
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String t, String p) {
        int n = t.length(), m = p.length();
        if (m == 0) return 0;
        int[][] dfa = new int[m][26];
        int x = 0;
        dfa[0][p.charAt(0) - 'a'] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < m; ++i) {
            for (int j = 0; j < 26; ++j) {
                    dfa[i][j] = dfa[x][j];
            }
			dfa[i][p.charAt(i) - 'a'] = i + 1;
            x = dfa[x][p.charAt(i) - 'a'];
        }
        for (int i = 0, j = 0; i < n && j < m; ++i) {
            j = dfa[j][t.charAt(i) - 'a'];
            if (j == m) return i - m + 1;
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```
The time complexity of this algorithm can be divided into two parts. First, the cost to build DFA table is ```O(Rm)``` where R is the number of characters. And in this case, ```R = 26```. The matching process cost O(n), we just loop once. Total complexity is ``` O(Rm + n) ```The bottleneck of this problem is the size of R. If it is too large, then the preprocess costs too much.

Second version: KMP with NFA(Nondeterministic Finite Automata). 
```
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String s, String p) {
        int m = p.length(), n = s.length();
        if (m == 0) return 0;
        int[] next = new int[m];
        next[0] = -1;
        for (int i = -1, j = 0; j < m - 1;) {
            if (i < 0 || p.charAt(i) == p.charAt(j)) {
                next[++j] = ++i;
            } else {
                i = next[i];
            }
        }
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < n && j < m) {
            if (j < 0 || s.charAt(i) == p.charAt(j)) {
                ++i;
                ++j;
            } else 
                j = next[j];
        }
        return j == m ? i - m : -1;
    }
}
```
In this case, NFA is used. And the time complexity is ```O(m + n)```.
Similar to path compression in Union Find, this can be further improved,
Third version is NFA with path compression.
The intuition is that if we move to next position and find that it is still the same as current, there is no need to do this comparison again. 

```
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String s, String p) {
        int m = p.length(), n = s.length();
        if (m == 0) return 0;
        int[] next = new int[m];
        next[0] = -1;
        for (int i = -1, j = 0; j < m - 1;) {
            if (i < 0 || p.charAt(i) == p.charAt(j)) {
                ++j; ++i;
                // path compression
                next[j] = p.charAt(i) != p.charAt(j) ? i : next[i];
            } else {
                i = next[i];
            }
        }
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < n && j < m) {
            if (j < 0 || s.charAt(i) == p.charAt(j)) {
                ++i;
                ++j;
            } else 
                j = next[j];
        }
        return j == m ? i - m : -1;
    }
}
```
This version improve the performance but it doesn't change the ```Big - O``` time and space complexity.

