Algorithm overview:
1. Generate the prefixes table. The prefixes table is a table with the same length as the needle. Each element `prefixes[i] ` represents the length of the longest prefix which is also a suffix from index 0 to i
2. Begin comparing the letters in `haystack` to the letters in `needle`. If it's a match, increment both pointers. Otherwise, consult the prefixes table to find the value at `n-1` where n is the index pointer for `needle`. We want to move `n` to the position at `prefixes[n-1]` because it represents the last character of an already matched prefix.

[This guy does a better job explaining. I know that sounded kind of convoluted.](http://https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BXCEFAzhxGY)

```
def strStr(self, haystack: str, needle: str) -> int:
	prefixes = [0] * len(needle) 
	i, j = 0, 1
	while j < len(needle):
		if needle[i] == needle[j]:
			prefixes[j] = i+1
			i += 1
			j += 1
		else:
			i = 0 if i == 0 else prefixes[i-1]
			if needle[i] != needle[j]:
				prefixes[j] = 0
				j += 1

	h, n = 0, 0
	while h < len(haystack) and n < len(needle):
		if haystack[h] == needle[n]:
			h += 1
			n += 1
		else:
			if n == 0:
				h += 1
			else:
				n = prefixes[n-1]

	return h - len(needle) if n == len(needle) else -1
```

