# Brute-Force Solution (100% Faster)

```c++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int strStr(string haystack, string needle) {
        int n = haystack.length();
        int l = needle.length();
        for(int i=0;i<=n-l;i++)
        {
            int j=0;
            for(;j<l;j++)
            {
                if(haystack[i+j]!=needle[j])
                {
                    break;
                }
            }
            if(j==l){return i;}
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$
The time complexity of the Brute-Force Approach is $$O(n*m)$$ where $$n$$ is the length of haystack & $$m$$ is the length of needle.
- Space Complexity: $$O(1)$$


# Optimal Approach (100% Faster)
We will be using Sliding windows to implement the famous KMP(Knuth-Morris-Patt) Algorithm for string matching.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int strStr(string haystack, string needle) {
        int n=haystack.size();
        int m=needle.size();
        int x=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            if(haystack[i]==needle[x])x++;
            else
            {
                i=i-x;
                x=0;
            }
            if(x==m)return i-x+1;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
The optimal approach uses Linear Time Complexity of $$O(n+m)$$ where nis the length of haystack & m is the length of needle

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
No extra Space utilized


