Naive solution (without use of KMP algorithm). Many solutions use `indexOf` and `substring` but I think that's too easy - it defeats the point of the problem. Note converting to a character arrary is faster than using `charAt` to index the string.

```
class Solution {
    public int strStr(String haystack, String needle) {
        if (needle.length() == 0) return 0;

        char[] haystackCharArray = haystack.toCharArray();
        char[] needleCharArrary = needle.toCharArray();
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < haystackCharArray.length) { // traverse haystack
            if (haystackCharArray[i] == needleCharArrary[j]) {
                j++; // the current characters are equal, increment the needle
            } else { // if not equal, reset needle progress, go backwards in haystack
                i -= j;
                j = 0;
            }
            i++; // increment the haystack, be careful of off by 1 erors here
            if (j == needleCharArrary.length) {
                return i - j; // return the current index minus the length of the needle (start of the needle in haystack) if we've found a match for evey character in needle in the haystack
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }
}
```

